text: I've been waiting for someone to do a movie about this! The town where this happened was Monroeville. The hometown where Harper Lee set the novel "To Kill A Mockingbird." They would put on plays of the book every year in Monroeville. They still sent a black man to death row because of police coercion and witness perjury. The only deviation from a perfect job that this true story does in exemplifing America is the happy ending.  However this movie seems to be celebrating the lawyer Bryan Stevenson, which obvious more people need to hear about.  The only problem with making a movie like that is that such a true story is already "Hollywood." The task for movie makers is to bring it down to earth and make it as real as the noses in front of people's faces. Case in point was "Heartbreak Ridge." Good movie but the dramatization of an already dramatic story which melodramatized a solid movie that could have been better.

text: People forget, or don't want to know, that our justice system isn't about revenge for the victims.  It's about fair treatment for the accused.  And this is because when our Constitution was written, the Salem hysteria was still fresh in people's minds.  There were still people around who'd seen what happens when people are accused of crimes with no proof, on just a word, and have no recourse or redress, and they were having none of that in their new country.  Yeah, it wasn't for everybody, because the society was different back then, and it's still not a level playing field, as this trailer shows.  But that was the _intention,_ and it's STILL the intention and the aspiration - fair representation for those accused, so that false accusations can't justify mob rule.

text: Just another example of how the media wants everyone to think that the jails are packed with innocent people, the police are incompetent and always arrest the wrong person and that the justice system doesn't work.  The reality is the police get the right person over 99.999% of the time, people that are innocent are few and far between and most of the cases of people being released decades after they were arrested and convicted is due to the prosecutors being unable to proceed to trial again on the person because most of the witnesses and/or evidence is unavailable for a new trial (and not because the person was actually innocent).  I'm not saying mistakes aren't made, but they are are far more the exception than the rule.  Not to mention the extensive number of people that are actually guilty, but their cases are dismissed on technicalities, pretrial issues that arise, or juries that find people not guilty because they watch too much TV and don't know what a trial and evidence are supposed to look like anymore.  Its not a perfect system, but its far from broken.
